The tide turned decisively in the 13th century with the theological genius
Thomas Aquinas denouncing homosexual acts as "against nature." All sex -
heterosexual and homosexual - was to be reserved only for married couples
open to procreation, and any other sexual activity was a grave sin.
Homosexuals, in the new theology, were part of nature â€” many had noticed
homosexual behavior in the animal kingdom, particularly among hares and
hyenas - but they were also somehow contrary to nature. Aquinas never
resolved this paradox. Neither has the [Catholic] church.
    --Andrew Sullivan, "The Gay Church." _New York_ magazine, 2019-01-21
      https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2019/01/gay-priests-catholic-church.html
